    %h1 Healing U.S. Healthcare
    %h3 How do we save an ailing system?
    %h3 By Cecile Lu and Neil Rens
.content-wrapper
  %article#background
    %p.p-slide
      $9,255
      =partial(footnote_link, :locals => {:footnotes=>footnotes, :href=>"http://www.cdc.gov/nchs/fastats/health-expenditures.htm", :text=>"Health Expenditures", :source=>"Centers for Disease Control and Prevention", :access=>"Web"})
      \. That’s how much your health costs the U.S. every year. You probably don’t pay that amount, let alone use that amount in health services. In fact, 10% of Americans account for more than 66% of healthcare consumption
      =partial(footnote_link, :locals => {:footnotes=>footnotes, :href=>"http://www.nihcm.org/images/Health_Care_Spending_Highly_Concentrated_CS2F2.png", :text=>"The Concentration of Health Care Spending", :source=>"NIHCM Foundation", :access=>"Web"})
      \. 
    %p.p-slide
      Nonetheless, you are entangled in the $2.9 trillion
      =partial(footnote_link, :locals => {:footnotes=>footnotes, :href=>"http://www.cdc.gov/nchs/fastats/health-expenditures.htm", :text=>"Health Expenditures", :source=>"Centers for Disease Control and Prevention", :access=>"Web"})
      our country spends on healthcare. 24%
      =partial(footnote_link, :locals => {:footnotes=>footnotes, :href=>"http://www.cbpp.org/research/policy-basics-where-do-our-federal-tax-dollars-go", :text=>"Policy Basics: Where Do Our Federal Tax Dollars Go?", :source=>"Center on Budget and Policy Priorities", :access=>"11 Mar. 2015. Web"})
      of the federal budget—your tax dollars—is part of this $2.9 trillion. You pay a lot, but what do you get, and how good is it?
    %p.p-slide
      Consider David. He just left his job as a high school teacher to launch an education-technology startup. With the change, he lost his health coverage, but that’s not worrying him. He’s healthy - why would he need health coverage? 
    %p.p-slide
      David is just one of the thousands of Americans facing these tough choices; he could be any one of us. But what happens if David’s gamble of good health fails him? Read on to follow David’s healthcare journey as he navigates the current system. Then, discover our vision for better healthcare in the U.S. and contribute your own ideas.
  %article#symptoms
    %h2 Symptoms
    %a{:name => "symptoms"}
    %p.p-slide
      Two weeks ago, David was going about his daily life. Today he is bedridden in a hospital, battling an infection he contracted in that hospital. In two weeks, he’ll be at home trying to figure out how to pay off his massive
      %span.slide#flip1{:data=>{:index => 1}} medical debt
      \. That’s if he’s lucky.
    .slide-panel{:data =>{:index=>1}}
      %p
        Medical debt refers to individual debt due to healthcare costs and related expenses. It is different from other debts because it is almost never accumulated by choice, and can add up quickly and unexpectedly. It can stem from any medical expenses, ranging from regular checkups to emergency room visits. Medical debt varies depending on insurance coverage and personal medical needs.
        =partial(footnote_link, :locals => {:footnotes=>footnotes, :href=>"https://www.debt.org/medical/", :text=>"Medical Debt Advice - Debt, Healthcare, Insurance & Medicare.", :source=>"Debtorg News", :access=>"Web"})
      %p
        In the U.S., medical debt accounts for more than 50% of all overdue debt that appears on credit reports. For 15 million people, medical debt is the only debt they have in collections in their credit report.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Medical Debt Is Ruining the Credit Scores of Millions of Americans", :href=>"http://www.washingtonpost.com/news/get-there/wp/2014/12/11/medical-debt-is-ruining-the-credit-score-of-millions-of-americans/", :source=>"Washington Post", :access=>"The Washington Post, 11 Dec. 2014. Web"})
    %p.p-slide
      How did he get here?
    %p.p-slide
      With the passage of the
      %span.slide#flip5{:data=>{:index => 5}} Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act (ACA)
      , David has to either purchase health insurance or pay a penalty tax each year.
    .slide-panel{:data =>{:index=>5}}
      %p
        The purpose of the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act (also known as ACA or Obamacare) is to “increase the number of Americans covered by health insurance and decrease the cost of healthcare.” Insurance companies are no longer allowed to deny people coverage and they can no longer revoke coverage when people get sick. People are no longer forced to pay extra for insurance because of pre-existing conditions.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"What Is Obamacare", :href=>"http://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2013/04/what-is-obamacare/274509/", :source=>"Hamblin, James", :access=>"The Atlantic. Atlantic Media Company, 2 Apr. 2013. Web"})
      %p
        To make insurance more accessible, the Affordable Care Act implemented Health Insurance Exchanges. The exchanges function as marketplaces for health insurance plans.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"ObamaCare | Health Insurance Exchange", :href=>"http://obamacarefacts.com/obamacare-health-insurance-exchange/", :source=>"Obamacare Facts", :access=>"Web"})
        Americans can use their state’s marketplace to obtain coverage from competing private healthcare providers. People can now compare prices of qualified health plans to choose the best fit in terms of coverage, premiums, and deductibles.
      %p
        The Affordable Care Act also implemented pay-for-performance incentives, which pays healthcare providers for outcomes instead of for services. While there have not been any adverse effects, the system has yet to show much evidence of success in improving patient outcomes.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Doubts About Pay-for-Performance in Healthcare", :href=>"https://hbr.org/2013/10/doubts-about-pay-for-performance-in-health-care", :source=>"Ryan, Andrew M., Rachel M. Werner", :access=>"Harvard Business Review, 9 Oct. 2013. Web"})
    = partial("features/us-healthcare/decision_point", :locals => {:index=>0} )
    .slide-panel{:data =>{:index=>2}}
      %p
        Bronze Plan coverage typically means that insurance companies pay for around 60% of covered healthcare expenses and the consumer pays for the rest. The Affordable Care Act requires insurance companies to offer Gold, Silver, and Platinum plans along with Bronze.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Bronze Plan – Affordable Care Act (Obamacare)", :href=>"http://www.healthpocket.com/individual-health-insurance/bronze-health-plans#.VaZx7hNVikp", :source=>"Obamacare Bronze Health Insurance Plans", :access=>"Web"})
        Each offers a tradeoff between premiums and deductibles.
      %p
        When the Affordable Care Act was first implemented, users spent hours on healthcare.gov before being able to purchase their insurance. The server was overwhelmed by the massive influx of information
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Here’s Everything You Need to Know about Obamacare’s Error-plagued Websites", :href=>"https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-switch/wp/2013/10/09/heres-everything-you-need-to-know-about-obamacares-error-plagued-web-sites/", :source=>"Washington Post", :access=>"The Washington Post, 9 Oct. 2013. Web"})
        the user interface was poorly designed and confusing to navigate,
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Not Fully Ready for Round Two", :href=>"http://www.thefiscaltimes.com/Articles/2014/07/31/Healthcaregov-Not-Fully-Ready-Round-Two", :source=>"Brianna Ehley", :access=>"The Fiscal Times, 31 Jul. 2014. Web"})
        and the cost calculator sometimes provided inaccurate information about subsidies.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Yet Another Obamacare Glitch Was Just Discovered", :href=>"http://www.thefiscaltimes.com/Articles/2014/03/21/Yet-Another-Obamacare-Glitch-Was-Just-Discovered", :source=>"Brianna Ehley", :access=>"The Fiscal Times, 21 Mar. 2014. Web"})
        The poor implementation may have caused some people, like David, to opt out of the plans in favor of the 2%* penalty tax.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Individual Mandate Penalty You Pay If You Don't Have Health Insurance Coverage", :href=>"https://www.healthcare.gov/fees-exemptions/fee-for-not-being-covered/", :source=>"HealthCare.gov", :access=>"Web"})
      %p
        Despite the slow start, 9 out of 10 Americans now have insurance. Prior to the implementation of the Affordable Care Act, only 8 out of 10 Americans were insured.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Nearly 90% of Americans Now Have Health Insurance", :href=>"http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/13/news/economy/obamacare-uninsured-gallup/", :source=>"CNNMoney", :access=>"Cable News Network. Web"})
      %p
        *In 2016 and onwards, the tax will be raised to 2.5%.
    %p.p-slide
      Without health insurance, David stops seeing his doctor. As a result, he also stops receiving vaccinations.
    %p.p-slide
      One day, David begins exhibiting flu-like symptoms. He assumes he will get better in a few days, but he doesn't. After a week, the symptoms continue to persist.
    %p.pslide
      What should David do?
      = partial("features/us-healthcare/decision_point", :locals => {:index=>1} )
    %p.p-slide
      Having no primary care doctor, David goes to the only place he thinks he can: an emergency department at a nearby hospital. It’s hard to find information about quality and cost of care at specific hospitals, so he simply picks the one closest to his home.
      = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Hospital Billing Varies Wildly, Government Data Shows", :href=>"http://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/08/business/hospital-billing-varies-wildly-us-data-shows.html?_r=0", :source=>"Meier, Barry, Jo Mcginty, and Julie Creswell", :access=>"The New York Times, 7 May 2013. Web"})
      = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Compare Hospitals Tool", :href=>"http://www.nerdwallet.com/health/hospitals/compare", :source=>"NerdWallet Health", :access=>"Web"})
  #cost-comparison-boston-container.chart-container
    %p 
      Pneumonia treatment costs in Boston range from $9,000 and $31,000
      = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Boston, Massachusetts: Simple Pneumonia & Pleurisy With Complications And Comorbities", :href=>"http://www.opscost.com/search?location=Boston%2C%20Massachusetts&drg_procedure_code=194", :source=>"OpsCost", :access=>"Web"})
