  %article#symptoms
    %p.p-slide
      After waiting for over an hour, David finally sees a doctor. David’s clinical presentation indicates influenza. While listening to David’s heart during the exam, the  doctor notices unusual rhythms. The doctor wants to check David's medical record to see if he has a history of arrhythmia.
    %p.p-slide
      Does the doctor have access to David's
      %span.slide#flip3{:data=>{:index => 3}} Electronic Health Record
      ?
    .slide-panel{:data =>{:index=>3}}
      %p
        An Electronic Health Record (EHR) contains the medical and treatment histories of patients and is designed to be inclusive of a broader view of a patient’s care. EHRs enable the sharing of information between multiple healthcare providers and organizations. They contain information from all clinicians involved in a patient’s care.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"What is an Electronic Health Record (EHR)", :href=>"http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/faqs/what-electronic-health-record-ehr", :source=>"HealthIT", :access=>"Web"})
        However, when EHRs became more widely implemented in 2004, the industry built hundreds of standalone systems to create and maintain EHRs.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Is Healthcare IT Interoperability (Almost) Here", :href=>"http://www.cio.com/article/2386750/vertical-industries/is-healthcare-it-interoperability-almost-here.html", :source=>"Eastwood, Brian", :access=>"CIO, 15 Apr. 2013. Web"})
        Within each system data is shared, but there is little to no data flow between different systems.
      %p
        Problems arise with the lack of interoperability between EHR systems. Approximately 40% of medical errors are directly related to information omissions and miscommunications. EHR systems do not share information with each other and they all present information in different ways. This causes misread charts, forgotten results, and untimely information during life-threatening crises.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Why I Hope to Help End EHRs Lack of Interoperability", :href=>"http://hitconsultant.net/2015/03/23/why-i-hope-to-help-end-ehrs-lack-of-interoperability/", :source=>"Voltz, Donald", :access=>"HIT Consultant, 22 Mar. 2015. Web"})
        Other hospitals hesitate to transfer data in fear of incurring liability for sharing private information.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"The Lack of Interoperability in the Healthcare Industry is an Enormous National Problem", :href=>"http://www.elxrhealth.com/lack-of-interoperability/", :source=>"ELXR Health", :access=>"5 June 2015. Web"})
      %p
        The 2009 Health Information Technology for Economic and Clinical Health (HITECH) Act promotes the adoption and meaningful use of health information technology such as EHRs.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Where Is HITECH's $35 Billion Dollar Investment Going", :href=>"http://healthaffairs.org/blog/2015/03/04/where-is-hitechs-35-billion-dollar-investment-going/", :source=>"Thune, John, Lamar Alexander, Pat Roberts, Richard Burr, Mike Enzi", :access=>"Health Affairs Blog, 4 Mar. 2015. Web"})
        Using money from the HITECH Act, the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) provide incentive payments to eligible professionals and hospitals. The CMS Medicare and Medicaid EHR Incentive Programs encourage adoption, implementation, upgrades and demonstration of meaningful use of certified EHR technology.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"EHR Incentive Programs", :href=>"http://www.cms.gov/Regulations-and-Guidance/Legislation/EHRIncentivePrograms/index.html?redirect=/EHRIncentivePrograms/", :source=>"CMS.gov: Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services", :access=>"Web"})
    %p.p-slide
    = partial("features/us-healthcare/decision_point", :locals => {:index=>2} )
    %p.p-slide
      Worried that the cardiac event could be related to David’s influenza, the doctor orders an ECG. The ECG shows an arrhythmia, but because the doctor does not know about David's previous diagnosis, he admits David for observation. Within the hour, David has a bed, is hooked up to a slew of monitoring equipment, and has a full blood panel done. These tests are unnecessary. Not only do they waste money, but they also reduce the efficiency of the healthcare system.
