    %p
      Nonrecommended statins cost more than $5 billion each year
      = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"\"Top 5\" Lists Top $5 Billion", :href=>"http://archinte.jamanetwork.com/article.aspx?articleid=1106007", :source=>"Kale MS, Bishop TF, Federman AD, Keyhani S.", :access=>"Arch Intern Med. 2011;171(20):1858-1859. doi:10.1001/archinternmed.2011.501. Web"})
    #waste-chart
  %article#symptoms
    %p.p-slide
      After two days at the hospital, leading to a $5,000 bill
      = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"How Much Does a Night in the Hospital Cost?", :href=>"https://www.trustedchoice.com/insurance-articles/life-health/cost-night-hospital/", :source=>"Trusted Choice Independent Insurance Agents", :access=>"17 Dec. 2013. Web"})
      , David’s fever spikes and he begins having chest pain. By the end of the week, a simple influenza admission turns into a case of
      %span.slide#flip4{:data=>{:index => 4}} hospital-acquired pneumonia
      \.
    .slide-panel{:data =>{:index=>4}}
      %p
        Hospital-acquired pneumonia is a lung infection that occurs during a hospital stay. Infections contracted at a hospital can be especially dangerous because of two reasons. First, patients are often already very sick and cannot fight off the germs. Second, the types of bacteria in hospitals are often more dangerous strains because they can be resistant to antibiotics.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Hospital-acquired Pneumonia: MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia", :href=>"http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/000146.html", :source=>"U.S National Library of Medicine", :access=>"U.S. National Library of Medicine. Web"})
        Pneumonia is one of the most common hospital-acquired infections, after urinary tract infections and wound infections. It has a 33% mortality rate, although the cause of death can be a combination of the pneumonia and other presenting illnesses.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Common Problems Patients Face in the Hospital", :href=>"http://www.webmd.com/a-to-z-guides/features/before-surgery-your-top-six-hospital-risks?page=3", :source=>"WebMD", :access=>"WebMD. Web"})
      %p
        440,000 patients die every year from preventable medical errors.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Medical Errors", :href=>"https://www.justice.org/what-we-do/advocate-civil-justice-system/issue-advocacy/medical-errors", :source=>"American Association for Justice", :access=>"Web"})
        Medical errors are the third leading cause of death in the United States, following cancer and heart disease.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Hospital Errors Are the Third Leading Cause of Death in U.S., and New Hospital Safety Scores Show Improvements Are Too Slow", :href=>"http://www.hospitalsafetyscore.org/newsroom/display/hospitalerrors-thirdleading-causeofdeathinus-improvementstooslow", :source=>"Hospital Safety Score", :access=>"23 Oct. 2013. Web"})
        Studies show that up to 12% of people going to a hospital will suffer severe harm as a result.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Medical Errors in America Kill More People than AIDS or Drug Overdoses. Here's Why", :href=>"http://www.vox.com/2015/1/29/7878731/medical-errors-statistics", :source=>"Kliff, Sarah", :access=>"Vox, 22 Apr. 2015. Web"})
      %p
        Medicare is now punishing hospitals with high rates of infections and other medical errors in an attempt to increase patient safety. Publicly funded hospitals have been penalized the most because they take care of sicker populations and deal with more complex cases.
        = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Teaching Hospitals Hit Hardest By Medicare Fines For Patient Safety", :href => "http://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2014/12/19/371862146/teaching-hospitals-hit-hardest-by-medicare-fines-for-patient-safety", :source=>"Rau, Jordan", :access=>"NPR. 19 Dec. 2014. Web"})
    %p.p-slide
      It doesn't have to be this way. If David had insurance, he probably would have received a flu shot. More opportunities for self-care would have saved David time and money. If the two EHRs had talked to each other, David likely would not have been admitted for an arrhythmia, and wouldn’t have developed hospital-acquired pneumonia.
