  %article#history
    %h2 History
    %a{:name => "history"}
    %p.p-slide
      Despite its shortcomings, the U.S. healthcare system also has strengths. Medical research, education, and technology flourish in the U.S. However, even these traditional strengths are facing challenges.
    .previous-successes
      .row
        .col-sm-4
          %h3 Research
          %p.centeredImage
            = image_tag "features/us-healthcare/research_icon-03.png", width: "50%", class: "centeredImage"
          %p
            49% of public research funding throughout the world comes from the U.S., amounting to $50.5B annually.
          %p
            However, U.S. spending on medical research has been increasing by less than the inflation rate since 2012. Not only is funding decreasing, but funding as a percentage of gross domestic product (GDP) is also decreasing.
            = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Restore the U.S. Lead in Biomedical Research", :href=>"http://jama.jamanetwork.com/article.aspx?articleid=2089336", :source=>"Dzau VJ, Fineberg HV", :access=>"JAMA. 2015;313(2):143-144. doi:10.1001/jama.2014.17660. Web"})
        .col-sm-4
          %h3 Education
          %p.centeredImage
            = image_tag "features/us-healthcare/education_icon-02.png", width: "50%", class: "centeredImage"
          %p
            According to U.S. News and World Reports, the U.S. has 8 of the top 10 medical schools in the world. 
            = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Best Global Universities for Clinical Medicine", :href=>"http://www.usnews.com/education/best-global-universities/clinical-medicine", :source=>"U.S. News", :access=>"U.S.News & World Report. Web"})
            It is also home to 17 of the top 20 hospitals.
            = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"World", :href=>"http://hospitals.webometrics.info/en/world", :source=>"Ranking Web of Hospitals", :access=>"Web"})
          %p
            However, the U.S. has fewer doctors per capita than most other industrialized nations.
            = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Health Resources: Doctors", :href=>"https://data.oecd.org/healthres/doctors.html", :source=>"OECD Statistics", :access=>"Web"})
        .col-sm-4
          %h3 Technology
          %p.centeredImage
            = image_tag "features/us-healthcare/tech_icon-03.png", width: "50%", class: "centeredImage"
          %p
            We have more MRI, CT, and PET machines per capita than any other country.
            = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"OECD Statistics", :href=>"http://stats.oecd.org/#", :source=>"OECD Statistics", :access=>"Web"})
          %p
            However, we spend significantly more on clinical care per capita than any other industrialized country.
    %p.p-slide
      A decade ago, the United States funded 57% of biomedical research around the globe. In 2015, the U.S. share has dropped down to 44%. Even though the U.S. still spends more than twice as much as any other country on medical research, federal spending is being cut
      = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"Bad Medicine", :href=>"http://www.economist.com/news/science-and-technology/21572735-cutting-american-health-research-will-harm-world-bad-medicine", :source=>"The Economist", :access=>"The Economist Newspaper, 2 Mar. 2013. Web"})
      and support for biomedical research in the U.S. is decreasing. Simultaneously, global interest in biomedical research is increasing
      = partial(footnote_link,:locals=>{:footnotes=>footnotes, :text=>"\"U.S. Funding of Health Research Stalls As Other Nations Rev Up.\"", :href => "http://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2015/01/13/376801357/u-s-funding-of-health-research-stalls-as-other-nations-rev-up", :source=>"Harris, Richard", :access=>"NPR, 13 Jan. 2015. Web"})
      , decreasing the percentage of America’s share in global research.

